This is the <strong>dependent variable</strong>.&nbsp;<br /><br />The variable on which it depends is the <strong>independent variable</strong>.&nbsp;<br /><br />To identify the independent variable, decide which variable stands alone and is dependent on nothing.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p><p>&nbsp;</p>","headerText":""},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0},"leftText":"<p>This graph from your electronics and grocery department manager shows the first quarter sales for this year.<br /><br />One of the variables is <em>time, </em>shown in months.&nbsp; Time is the independent variable.<br /><br />To identify the dependent variable, decide which variable is changing based on the independent variable.<br /><br />In this graph, the value for sales is changing based on the month during which it is measured. &nbsp; Sales is the dependent variable. &nbsp;&nbsp;<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":1,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0},"leftText":"<p>The first quarter sales report provided by the electronics and grocery department manager is a <strong>line graph</strong>.<br /><br />A <strong>line graph</strong> shows data as a collection of points connected by straight lines.<br /><br />It is used to show changes in data over time and for comparing different sets of data that share the same independent variable.<br /><br />The independent variable values are almost always shown at the bottom of the line graph, and the dependent variables are shown&nbsp; Then read left to the values that represent the dependent variable.<br /><br />Note that sales are given in $100,000.&nbsp; This means that a 3 represents $300,000.<br /><br />At the end of February, sales for the grocery department were at $300,000.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"Reading line Graphs:  finding values"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0},"leftText":"<p>You also want to know when grocery sales were at their lowest, and what the sales amount was.<br /><br />Look at the green line representing grocery sales and find its lowest point.<br /><br />Read to the left to find that the lowest sales point was 1.5 or $150,000.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<br /><br />Read down to find that this occurred at the beginning of April.<br />&nbsp;</p>","rightText":"<p><span class=\"marker\">(placeholder)</span><br /><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0},"leftText":"<p>Now you need to analyze the months during which sales were increasing, decreasing, and constant for each department.&nbsp; You can determine this from the shape of the line.<br /><br />If the independent variable is on the bottom of the graph, read the graph from left to right.<br /><br />If the line slants <strong>upwards</strong> from left to right, the value of the dependent variable is <strong>increasing</strong>.<br /><br />If the line slants <strong>downward</strong> from left to right, the value of the dependent variable is <strong>decreasing</strong>.<br /><br />If the line is <strong>flat</strong> or <strong>horizontal</strong>, the value of the dependent variable is<strong> constant</strong>.</p>","rightText":"<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"data:image/png;base64,\" /></p>","headerText":"Reading line graphs:  increasing, decreasing and constant values"},{"settings":{"showAudio":1,"showNext":1,"showHeader":0,"hideRightPanel":0,"delayStep":0,"delayRight":0,"fullWhiteboard":0},"leftText":"<p>For the electronics department, the blue line representing sales is rising in February and April.&nbsp;
